<div class="ru-top-story">
<h6 class="kicker"></h6>
<div class="ru-story">
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/23/morning-agenda-lenovo-in-deal-for-ibms-server-unit/" data-title="Lenovo in Deal for IBM&#8217;s Server Unit" data-description="Lenovo to buy IBM&#039;s low-end server business. | Overseas banks may soon have to raise capital against potential losses for their American units. | A doctor displays faulty memory in SAC insider trading trial. | @GSElevator book to test the appetite for Wall Street exposÃ©s. | Icahn takes to Twitter.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Lenovo announced on Thursday that it would <b>acquire IBMâs low-end server business for $2.3 billion</b>, signaling the successful completion of a deal that fell through a year ago, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/23/lenovo-buys-ibm-server-business-for-2-3-billion">Neil Gough and David Gelles write in DealBook.</a></b> The server unit, which includes IBMâs x86 server business, brings in an estimated $5 billion in revenue a year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Lenovo said it would settle the transaction with $2 billion in cash and the balance in its own Hong Kong-listed shares.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last year, Lenovo, which is based in China, and IBM were in talks about the server business, but the deal fell through when the two companies could not agree on a price. But Lenovoâs reticence seems to have paid off for the company. Dell and Fujitsu had expressed interest in buying the unit earlier this week, but because Lenovo had spent time last year analyzing the business, <b>it was able to make a quick offer that IBM was happy with</b>.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> LOOPHOLE FOR FOREIGN BANKS MAY CLOSE <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> For three years, overseas banks like Barclays, Deutsche Bank and Credit Suisse have not had to comply with parts of the Dodd-Frank Act, which aims to limit banksâ potential losses on loans and trades, simply because they were foreign. But this loophole may soon close, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/22/exporting-u-s-rules-for-foreign-banks">Peter Eavis writes in DealBook.</a></b></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Dodd-Frank can cause trepidation among bank executives because the rule requires banks to maintain a level of capital that would cover losses, which can weaken the measures of profitability that Wall Street obsesses over. The closing of the loophole is <b>rankling many European banks</b>, which have never had to report their American capital positions before and thus have been exempt from maintaining the same level of financial buffer.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Opponents of the plan argue that the rule is detrimental to European banks because they will have to infuse their American units with large amounts of capital rather than set aside capital for their firms as a whole. Still, supporters claim the new foreign bank rules will create a level playing field for American banks and their European counterparts.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">DOCTORâS FAULTY MEMORY ON DISPLAY AT SAC TRIAL <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Dr. Sidney Gilman, the governmentâs star witness in the insider trading trial against Mathew Martoma, a former portfolio manager at SAC Capital Advisors, showed signs of his age on Wednesday, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/22/details-slip-by-insider-trials-main-witness">Matthew Goldstein and Alexandra Stevenson write in DealBook</a></b>. âThere still remain <b>some holes in my memory,</b>&#8221; said Dr. Gilman, who is 81.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On the witness stand for the third day, Dr. Gilman told the jury that he recalled only two weeks ago the full details of Mr. Martomaâs visit to his office at the University of Michigan in July 2008. The meeting, during which Dr. Gilman said he relayed confidential information to Mr. Martoma about the results of a drug trial that had not yet been released, is central to the governmentâs claim that Dr. Gilman helped Mr. Martoma devise the largest insider trading scheme in history. During his cross-examination, which will continue on Thursday, <b>Dr. Gilman at times took long pauses before answering questions.</b> At other points, he asked the defense lawyer to repeat the question.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Martomaâs lawyers sought to <b>discredit Dr. Gilman during opening statements</b>, when they accused the prosecution of building a case âriddled with inconsistencies.â One lawyer brought up the fact that Dr. Gilman had been taking a drug known to cause confusion as part of the cancer treatment he was undergoing in the years he and Mr. Martoma were communicating.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> The <b>World Economic Forum</b> continues in Davos, Switzerland. <b>Weekly jobless claims</b> are out at 8:30 a.m. The <b>PMI Manufacturing Index</b> for January is released at 8:58 a.m. <b>Existing home sales</b> for December and the <b>Federal Housing Finance Agency&#8217;s house price index</b> for November are out at 10 a.m. <b>Starbucks</b> releases fourth-quarter earnings after the market closes. <b>Michael S. Dell</b>, the chief executive of Dell Inc., and <b>Stephen A. Schwarzman</b>, founder and chief executive of the Blackstone Group, are on Bloomberg TV at 7 a.m. and 10 a.m., respectively. Treasury Secretary <b>Jacob J. Lew</b> is on Bloomberg TV at 4 p.m.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> @GSELEVATOR BOOK TO TEST TELL-ALL APPETITE <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> The Twitter parody account @GSElevator, which claims to post anonymous snippets overheard in the Goldman Sachs elevators, will have a new venue for its snark. The anonymous author of the account has signed a book deal with Touchstone, an imprint of Simon &#038; Schuster, which announced the deal on Wednesday, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/22/a-tell-all-born-from-goldman-gossip">Julie Bosman reports in DealBook.</a></b> The book will be called âStraight to Hell: True Tales of Deviance and Excess in the World of Investment Banking.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The author, who writes under the name J.T. Stone, said in an email that he aimed to <b>âshowcase and illuminate the true culture of Wall Street</b> as I have experienced it.â He is âvery confident,â he wrote, in his âability to deliver a best-seller.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ICAHN TAKES TO TWITTER <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Carl C. Icahn sent out a series of Twitter messages on Wednesday about his position in Apple, causing a familiar stir in the markets. âHaving purchased $500 million more $AAPL shares in the last two weeks, <b>our investment has crossed the $3 billion mark</b> yesterday,â Mr. Icahn posted just after 10:30 a.m. About a minute later, he sent a post on his disappointment in Appleâs board for not increasing its share buyback program.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Icahnâs use of Twitter to publicize his investment activities <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/10/07/business/media/using-twitter-to-move-the-markets.html">is nothing new.</a></b> On Oct. 1, he posted a message about having dinner with Timothy D. Cook, Apple&#8217;s chief executive, which resulted in a spike in the price of Apple shares. His tweets on Wednesday produced a similar outcome, with shares <b><a href="//www.reuters.com/article/2014/01/22/us-apple-icahn-idUSBREA0L1ED20140122">increasing by as much as 1.5 percent</a></b> during the day. Shares in Apple closed on Wednesday at $551.51.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIf I want people to know what Iâm doing, Iâll go on Twitter, and <b>Iâll tell my followers about it,</b>â Mr. Icahn said on CNBC a few hours after sending his messages.</p>
</div>
